<h2>The question</h2>
<p>Epic <a href="/backlog/2079-author-w3c-spec-shaped-normative-standards-for-every-we-stan/">#2079</a> wants a
W3C-spec-shaped normative write-up — MUST/MUST-NOT conformance language, conformance classes, a typed error model,
interface definitions — for every in-scope WE standard. No such surface exists today: zero RFC-2119 language in any
of the 279 registry entries. Decision <a href="/backlog/2096-spec-register-home-skeleton-house-style-and-scope-policy-for/">#2096</a>
must settle three things before any authoring wave runs: <strong>where the normative document lives</strong> (the home + form),
<strong>what register it is written in</strong> (skeleton + house style), and <strong>which standards owe one, when</strong>
(scope + maturity policy). This topic is the prior-art survey those forks stand on.</p>

<h2>How the real spec ecosystems do it</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Ecosystem</th><th>Home / artifact</th><th>House style &amp; tooling</th><th>Maturity coupling</th></tr>
  <tr>
    <td>W3C / WICG</td>
    <td>One spec document per standard, distinct from its <em>explainer</em></td>
    <td>Bikeshed / ReSpec generate the conformance boilerplate, style RFC-2119 keywords, validate inline WebIDL, autolink <code>&lt;dfn&gt;</code> terms cross-spec; conformance classes named per SpecGL (user agent · author · authoring tool)</td>
    <td>ED → WD → CR → PR → REC; CR requires complete normative text + implementation experience</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>WHATWG</td>
    <td>One evergreen <em>living standard</em> per domain, edited in place</td>
    <td>Numbered algorithms per the Infra standard's conventions; typed error model ("throw a <code>TypeError</code>", "throw a <code>NotFoundError</code> <code>DOMException</code>"); WebIDL blocks</td>
    <td>Living document — no versioned snapshots; history is the commit trail</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>TC39</td>
    <td>Per-proposal repo: README explainer + an ecmarkup normative document, merged into ECMA-262 at stage 4</td>
    <td>ecmarkup (<code>emu-clause</code>/<code>emu-alg</code>/<code>emu-grammar</code>) — structured algorithm steps, its own notation (not WebIDL)</td>
    <td>Spec text is a <em>stage-entry requirement</em>: initial text at stage 2, complete at 2.7, tests + implementations before 4</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>IETF</td>
    <td>One RFC per document, immutable once published</td>
    <td>xml2rfc / kramdown-rfc; fixed skeleton (Abstract · Requirements Language citing BCP&nbsp;14 = RFC&nbsp;2119 + 8174 · body · Security Considerations · IANA Considerations)</td>
    <td>Versioning via Obsoletes/Updates chains — the model WE's research-topic supersession already copies</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Design systems / component ecosystems</td>
    <td>WAI-ARIA APG patterns (guidance, distinct from the normative ARIA spec); Open UI per-component research → proposal (anatomy · states · behaviors · keyboard); per-component spec markdown files in library repos</td>
    <td>Prose + tables + TypeScript-ish signatures; <strong>no</strong> RFC-2119 register, <strong>no</strong> implementor error model</td>
    <td>None — guidelines track releases, not conformance maturity</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h2>Cross-ecosystem laws (what the survey forces)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Explainer ≠ spec.</strong> Every mature ecosystem publishes the normative document as its own artifact with its own URL — never a section grafted into the introductory prose. WE's existing block/plug descriptions and intent <code>description</code> fields are explainers in this taxonomy.</li>
  <li><strong>The register is enforced by construction.</strong> Bikeshed/ReSpec/ecmarkup/xml2rfc make the skeleton and boilerplate a template the author cannot vary. The WE analogue is a fixed spec-skeleton partial + a gate, not a style guide agents are asked to remember.</li>
  <li><strong>Every requirement is addressed to a named conformance class.</strong> The WE mapping falls straight out of the constellation: <em>implementation</em> (FUI or any vendor building the contract) vs <em>document/author</em> (a page using the standard) — the WE↔FUI boundary made into spec vocabulary, which keeps every MUST on the observable side of the boundary.</li>
  <li><strong>RFC 8174 over bare 2119</strong>: keywords are normative only in ALL CAPS — essential for prose-heavy pages that use lowercase "must" informally.</li>
  <li><strong>The platform's error model is typed-and-named.</strong> "These cases are valid; these throw this named error" is exactly the ratified #2074 conformance-table shape — WE already has the house error-model template.</li>
  <li><strong>Spec text is owed at a maturity stage, never at concept stage.</strong> TC39 and W3C both make normative text an entry requirement of a stage; nobody writes MUST prose for a stage-0 sketch. Direct precedent for exempting <code>concept</code> registry entries.</li>
  <li><strong>A typed-error conformance register would genuinely differentiate WE</strong> — design systems and component libraries publish guidelines and API references, not implementor-conformance specs; only ARIA/Open UI come close and neither ships an error model.</li>
</ul>

<h2>In-repo ground truth — the four surfaces today</h2>
