<p>Two mechanical facts shape the home fork: <code>audit-trail</code> exists as both a block and a protocol (and
<code>action</code>-family ids recur across categories), so a flat per-standard keyspace collides —
any new collection must be <strong>category-qualified</strong>. And the wiring pattern for a gated one-file-per-entry
collection already exists twice: the research topics (one JSON per topic + one description partial per topic +
a size-1 pagination template, with the description partial required by <code>check:standards</code>) and the
block/plug description gates. A new top-level route additionally needs its segment added to the Vite dev-proxy
allowlist (gate-checked).</p>

<h2>Statutes already on this turf</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Constellation placement / zero-impl</strong> — WE holds definitions only; a normative spec is pure definition, so the register is WE-side by construction and its conformance classes bind implementations elsewhere.</li>
  <li><strong>One authoring source-of-truth; serializable forms are derived projections</strong> — forbids a second normative home per standard; settles "structured JSON conformance field" as a possible <em>later derived projection</em> of the prose home, never a rival authoring home.</li>
  <li><strong>Intents are UX-only</strong> — the intent's inline description cannot carry the normative register; an intent's spec must live elsewhere and confine itself to the UX contract (dimensions, values, observable states), with block compliance judged per <em>intent-conformance-is-block-compliance</em>.</li>
  <li><strong>Mandate the surface contract, not the computation</strong> — a WE standard normatively pins the observable surface contract, never the computation behind it; the register's requirements section must encode this bound (no Infra-style internal processing models).</li>
  <li><strong>Non-verdict conformance compares by a closed matcher vocabulary</strong> — the conformance-vector suite is already the machine-readable conformance surface; the spec's prose error table cross-references the vectors, never duplicates them.</li>
  <li><strong>Refine in place</strong> (design-first) + the research-topic supersession model — together they already answer "living spec vs dated snapshots": specs are living; the dated audit trail lives in reports/research.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Synthesis → the #2096 forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fork 1 (home)</strong>: a new one-file-per-standard normative spec collection — category-qualified partials + size-1-paginated detail pages, gate-required per the lifecycle-derived scope rule (no new registry field). The spec partial becomes the standard's <em>single</em> normative home: existing surfaces keep explainer prose and transclude/link it (a migration clause deliberately superseding the protocol-body-in-project-page rule, with lineage). In-place authoring is rejected on register-uniformity merit (an intent's register would sit inside a statute-capped inline JSON HTML string; a protocol's inside another page's section); "structured JSON as the home" cannot carry conformance prose — the machine-readable half stays with the conformance-vector suite.</li>
  <li><strong>Fork 2 (skeleton + house style)</strong>: a house-adapted W3C register — fixed section skeleton (status line · non-normative intro · Conformance with BCP-14 boilerplate + the two named classes · Terminology bound to the glossary · interface definitions · <em>observable</em> behavior requirements (surface contract only, never internal computation) · the conformance-case + typed-error table cross-referenced to the vectors · web-standards alignment · lineage), with <strong>TypeScript in a defined declaration subset</strong> (interfaces/type aliases, method + property signatures, union/literal types, readonly; throws live in the error table) as the single interface notation. Full WebIDL is an engine-binding notation whose distinguishing semantics WE's JS-level contracts don't exercise (a derived WebIDL translation is the artifact at an actual standards-body submission); a keyword-sprinkle with no fixed skeleton cannot be gated and has no conformance spine.</li>
  <li><strong>Fork 3 (scope + maturity)</strong>: the spec obligation derives from the one lifecycle badge — <code>active</code> ⇒ required (an explicit, owned amendment of the promotion bar; the 76 current actives are the migration work-list), <code>draft</code>/<code>experimental</code> ⇒ permitted and required-for-promotion (encoded by authoring the partial early — no sub-states), <code>concept</code> ⇒ exempt (normative prose over unratified design fabricates requirements; universal stub specs are refuted as a redundant encoding that dilutes the register). Census: 76 specs owed at the active tier (39 blocks, 6 intents, 31 plugs, 0 protocols). Pilot <a href="/backlog/2097-pilot-normative-spec-customnoderegistry-2074-in-the-ratified/">#2097</a> = CustomNodeRegistry, settled by enumeration: the only standard whose conformance spine (#2074's typed-error table) is already ratified — noting it still needs its plug registry entry minted (at draft/experimental, so the pilot exercises the permitted arm; the required arm lands with wave 1).</li>
</ul>
